{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511603"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:43:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:43:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11760"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11760"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.03,0.03,0.11,0.78]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4373"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43548"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4373"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11760"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28561"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9160"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6094"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43548"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of increasing periumbilical pain. He has no other symptoms. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes, osteoarthritis of both knees and intermittent heartburn. His medications include metformin and across-the-counter antacids PRN. He has a 10 pack-year smoking history and drinks four cans of beer a day. On examination, his pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, temperature 37.4\u00b0C and BMI 36 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Apart from the region shown in the photograph (Image), his abdomen is soft and distended. The lump is exquisitely tender and irreducible.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Antibiotics and review","Manual reduction","Percutaneous aspiration","Incision and drainage","Surgical exploration"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a strangulated paraumbilical hernia. This patient has couple of risk factors such as obesity and smoking history which could cause chronic cough (smoker\u0027s cough). Anything that increases intra-abdominal pressure increase the risk of developing an abdominal hernia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth irreducible and strangulated hernia cannot be reduced manually. However the difference is that strangulated hernia often presents with tenderness, erythematous and warm to touch overlying skin. Also cough impulse could be used to differentiate between the two where cough impulse may be present for irreducible hernia but not for strangulated hernias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical exploration\u003C/strong\u003E for strangulated hernias is required urgently to assess the viability of the tissue that has been strangulated as it could be ischemic and necrotic. Dead bowel has to be resected should it be deemed unsalvageable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E could be given if the strangulated hernia was serious enough to cause systemic features such as fever or even signs of sepsis. However prophylactic IV broad-spectrum antibiotics could be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EManual reduction\u003C/strong\u003E will not reduce the hernia in this case\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoth percutaneous aspiration \u003C/strong\u003Eand\u003Cstrong\u003E incision \u0026amp; drainage\u003C/strong\u003E are not definitive treatment options for paraumbilical hernia. Abscess from strangulated hernia could be drained. This could be better visualised using CT abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Strangulated or obstructed hernia is a surgical emergency therefore prompt recognition and treatment is required."],"references":["LeBlanc KA, Kingsnorth AN, Sanders DL, editors. Management of abdominal hernias. Springer International Publishing; 2018."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28561"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11760"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15491"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15491"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5e9fcc60-81bf-4ba9-b88e-58e106c17571.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5e9fcc60-81bf-4ba9-b88e-58e106c17571.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28561"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-22T13:27:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-22T13:27:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4373"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43548"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management"